deck: Genos is a 19-year old cyborg and one of the main protagonists of One-Punch Man. He is the self-proclaimed disciple of Saitama, as well as a hero under the hero association. He is currently serving as S-Class rank 14 and goes by the alias "Demon Cyborg"
description:
Origin

4 years before the start of the series, Genos was a regular boy who lived in a small town. Then one day, out of nowhere, a random, psychotic cyborg attacked Genos's hometown- completely destroying it and killing Genos's family in the process. Afterwards, a scientist for justice named Dr. Kuseno passed by through the town looking for the cyborg. Genos then begged Dr. Kuseno to transform him into a cyborg in order to help track down the one that murdered his family and destroyed his town. The doctor agreed, and ever since then Genos has been hunting down evil organization and fighting for justice.

Appearance

Genos is a youthful looking young man with an entirely mechanical body. He as spiky ash-blonde hair and purely black eyes with yellow irises. He also has two silver piercings and normally wears tank tops and jeans with black or brown boots. He has received several different mechanical upgrades throughout the series, each one changing his appearance drastically.

Personality

Genos is a very determined man with a strong sense of justice who is constantly striving to become stronger. Because of his resolve and history, he will do whatever it takes to become more powerful. This leads him to greatly respect Saitama and frequently ask him to train him.

Genos usually serves as comic relief to Saitama's actions, especially during battles or simply when referring to his baldness. He stays with Saitama out of belief he will become stronger, and greatly respects him. However, Genos is a serious character and there are times when if he feels annoyed or bewildered he will lash out, such as when Saitama explained the source of his power. Moments like this highlight Genos's level headed qualities, and the fact that he is willing to do anything to become stronger, even if it is to turn against his master.

Genos also has the tendency to either underestimate his opponents in battle, or let his guard down. This was shown his battle with Deep Sea King and Carnage Kabuto. He also has a sense of respect for himself, and feels disappointed whenever he fails to reach a goal, such as in his battle with Mosquito Girl or his attempt to stop the meteor from falling on Z-City.

Powers and Abilities

Genos is incredibly powerful, being not only an S-Class hero, but a genius fighter with large battle experience and several techniques. Despite these things however, a running gag in One Punch Man is Genos's struggle to battle powerful characters, only for all of them to get defeated by Saitama in one punch.

Cyborg Physiology

Genos has an entirely mechanical body that's been equipped with combat-ready cybernetic modifications. These include several weapons and canons, as well as sensors, scannors, and boosters. These cyborg enhancements enable Genos with vast amounts of super strength, speed, durability, and stamina.

Superhuman Strength

Genos has immense physical strength, and is capable of obliterating the face of a cliff with a flurry of punches. He was seen cracking bedrock with a simple drop kick, and was able to trade blows with someone as powerful as the Deep Sea King, who earlier blew a hole through a nuke shelter with ease.

Superhuman Speed

Genos is extremely fast, being able to keep up with a casual Saitama (albeit for a short while) the latter who is in the same speed tier as Boros. He was also keeping up with Speed O' Sonic, who is massively hypersonic and among the fastest characters in the series.

Superhuman stamina and durability

Was able to keep fighting perfectly well despite losing an arm, fought after having his neck broken by Carnage Kabuto, and tanked the air pressure from a "death" punch from Saitama (the same air pressure which annihilated the landscape behind him)
name: Demon Cyborg

deck: A teenage girl who was revealed to be an Inhuman after being exposed to the Terrigen Mists.
description:
Origin

Fiona was a normal girl until the city of Attilan fell and the Terrigen Mists were released. It was then that she discovered that she had Inhuman ancestry and experienced Terrigenesis. After her transformation, she experienced both cyber-bullying and physical bullying and was about to commit suicide when several teenage heroes interrupted and saved her.

Creation

Fiona was created by writer Matt Kindt and artist Paul Davidson. She first appeared in Inhumanity: The Awakening #1.

Major Story Arcs

Inhumanity

Fiona was an ordinary high school girl prior to Thanos' invasion of Earth. When he did invade, he attacked Black Bolt, believing him to know the location of his son, Thane. In an act of defiance against the mad titan, Black Bolt attacked him and caused the Inhuman city of Attilan to fall from the sky. Black Bolt's attack also charged a bomb that released the mutative terrigen mists across Earth. Individuals, such as Fiona, who had Inhuman blood in their veins went into Terrigenesis Cocoon and emerged as Inhumans.

Fiona's transformation gave her an avian appearance which initially disgusted her due to the negative comments posted about her online. She was even physically attacked by several of her brother's friends and, overcome with depression, she decided to kill herself. She flew up into the air as high as she could manage, tied her wings behind her back, and allowed herself to plummet back to Earth.

Luckily, Pixie was following her online activity and teleported to her home with Quentin Quire, Finesse, and Striker just in time to save her. The teen heroes talk her down and convince her that she isn't a freak. She thanks them and ask if they will talk to her brother, Flynn, who also underwent Terregensis and was having a hard time dealing with it. When they arrived at his room, the cocoon had hatched and a massive hole punctured the ceiling. The local news revealed that a meteor had landed nearby, but it was then shown to be Flynn reveling in his newfound powers.
name: Fiona

Inhumanity

The bomb unleashed Terrigen Mists which all the humans on Earth who had Inhuman blood to experience Terrigenesis by entering a Terrigenesis Cocoon. They entered human and emerged with new powers and appearances.

Flynn was one of those new Inhumans, much like his sister. When Fiona decided to kill herself as a result of being bullied, Pixie, Finesse, Quentin Quire, and Striker arrived and helped her acclimate to her new abilities. Fiona took the heroes to Flynn's room to help him as well, but he was gone, leaving only a giant hole in the ceiling.

deck: An Atlantean member of the New Warriors, and Warrior Handmaiden to Lady Namora, Princess-Regent of Atlantis.
description:
Origin

Faira Sar Namora appeared to the New Warriors Scarlet Spider and Hummingbird, after witnessing the slaughter of a number of her people by the Evolutionaries sent by the High Evolutionary to wipe out genetic aberrations (including mutants, Inhumans, Atlanteans, those who have been "corrupted" by magic, and those whose molecular structures have been altered by science). Codenamed Water Snake, Faira is the warrior-handmaiden of Aquaria Neptunia, aka Lady Namora, the Princess-Regent of Atlantis and cousin to the king. As such, Faira enjoys an elevated status among the Atlantean peoples. She had been sent out by Namora with a party of Atlantean warriors to find the supposedly dead Namorita. The mystics of Atlantis had detected her reemergence, and so Faira was sent to retrieve her. On the way, the Evolutionaries cut them off, and killed every last one of them, except for Faira, who managed to survive the attack.

New Warriors

Faira joined the New Warriors on their quest to defeat the High Evolutionary and his plan to wipe out all genetic aberrations. Joining Justice, Speedball, Scarlet Spider, Hummingbird, Sun Girl, Haechi, Nova, and Silhouette, Faira managed to stop the Evolutionary's evil plot. She became a permanent member of the New Warriors during their future conflicts.

Powers & Abilities:

Water Snake has displayed the ability to control water, known as hydrokinesis. She can form objects from the water she is controlling. She is a very skilled combatant, and has proven her skill, and lethally so, with a special trident she uses in battle. As an Atlantean, she has a denser bone structure than normal humans, granting her enhanced stamina, strength, and speed. She can also breathe and survive underwater.

Origin

Married Mr. Carter Dudley and inherited his fortune. She was wise with her money and now has to avoid her late husband's family, which has not been money-wise. Of note, she has disinherited Earle Dudley, a young man that tries to woo every assistant that Mrs. Dudley hires.

Major Story Arcs

To avoid family and to take advantage of her fortune, Mrs. Carter Dudley travels extensively. While doing so with her latest assistant Arlene, Mrs. Dudley decides to leave all her wealth to Arlene. She knows Arlene and Earle are secretly dating so she requests that she and Arlene travel to Italy to prevent Earle trying to marry Arlene (as Mrs. Dudley has informed him of her desires to give everything to Arlene). While on the boat to Italy, Mrs. Dudley learns that Arlene will be engaged to Kirk Martingale and that they are to be married when the boat docks. She supposedly travels around Europe with the two for their honeymoon.

Origin

An elderly gentleman attendee of a salesmen convention.

Major Story Arcs

While at his convention's party, Mr. Grant is delighted to spend time with Carol Scott, a new (albeit reluctant) party girl. He tells her that she makes him feel nearly fifty years younger. The two go off to talk and Mr. Grant falls asleep on the sofa. He is awakened by an undercover detective named Phil Wayne. The detective wants to make sure that Carol hasn't stolen anything, as he saw her sneaking away from the sleeping man. Mr. Grant is pleased to announce that Carol is innocent of any wrongdoing. (She had merely been trying to get away without waking the elderly man.)

deck: Personal assistant to Mrs. Carter Dudley and secret paramour to Mrs. Dudley's nephew, Earle Dudley.
description:
Origin

Arlene began dating Earle Dudley around the time that he was fired from managing his aunt's estate. Arlene and Earle have to keep their love a secret for fear that Arlene will also be fired as Mrs. Carter Dudley's personal assistant since Mrs. Dudley practically hates her nephew by now.

Major Story Arcs

As part of her job, Arlene accompanies Mrs. Dudley to the ski resort Sun Valley. The only free time she gets is in the morning and one day she decides to go skiing. As she's out, she collides with a man. She is shocked when he compliments her beauty, kisses her, then speeds off. Arlene returns to Mrs. Dudley and learns that they are off to Palm Beach. Arlene makes the arrangements and gets everything onboard a plane. There, she sees a magazine with the man on the cover. He is Kirk Martingale and he seems to be a playboy that is already engaged to another celebrity.

During their stay in Palm Beach, Arlene gets a letter from Earle asking about the possibility of visiting. Arlene asks Mrs. Carter Dudley if she wouldn't like to Earle one last time. This is instantly shot down. Arlene then takes a walk on the beach and runs into Kirk. He pleads for her to get to know him but she has not desire to. She recalls his engagement to another celebrity; he explains that the pictures in the magazines are a publicity stunt put on by an old flame. She returns to the hotel and finds a telegraph from Earle - he wants to meet up with her in Florida and marry her immediately. She wouldn't be around to see him, as Mrs. Dudley has Arlene book a cruise to Italy.

On the ship, Mrs. Dudley admits to Arlene that she wrote to Earle that he was out of her will and that all her belongings would pass to Arlene. Arlene is speechless. Mrs. Dudley then explains that she wanted to leave the United States because she knew Earle would try to marry Arlene right away. Arlene is confused and walks away to get some air. She begins to see Earle's trickery and decides that she is better off without him. Then Kirk walks up and the two agree to marry when they land.

deck: A private detective.
description:
Origin

As a private detective, Phil is occasionally hired to work conventions and parties as extra security.

Major Story Arcs

At a salesmen convention, Phil spots Carol Scott tiptoeing away from a sleeping Anthony Grant. He immediately grabs her and questions her about whether she stole from Mr. Grant. The old man awakens and exonerates Carol. Phil is then slapped before Carol leaves. Smitten, Phil follows Carol home and confronts her about his feelings for her. He begs for her number and calls her incessantly. He finally lands a date and the two begin an odd relationship in which they seem to be totally in love.

All seems to be going well except that Phil has to cancel dates frequently due to his job. He even cancels a date on Carol's birthday. He is surprised to see her that night at a party he is working. (She attends with Mildred as a way to lash out at Phil.) He is even more surprised to learn that she is suspected of killing a man named Cunningham. He claims responsibility for her while the body is taken in for an autopsy. He and Carol are relieved to hear that Cunningham died of a heart attack and not from anything Carol had done. The two settle down.

deck: A girl who continually makes rash decisions.
description:
Origin

A normal girl living with her friend Mildred.

Major Story Arcs

Carol ribs Mildred for coming home late but learns that her roommate has taken a job as a party girl. Carol warns against the job but is shocked to learn that Mildred makes really good money her first night. She accompanies Mildred to meet George Godfrey, a party girl supplier. Carol reluctantly agrees to attend a salesmen's convention and dances with an elderly gentleman named Mr. Grant. He gets so tired that he falls asleep and she tries to tiptoe away without waking him. She is grabbed and accused of being a thief. Mr. Grant awakens and states that nothing has been taken and Carol is released. She slaps the man across the face and storms out of the party.

Carol walks home to vent some of her anger. The man from the party catches up to her and introduces himself as Phil Wayne, a private detective that works parties to protect attendees. He explains that he has fallen for Carol and hopes to see her again. Carol doubts it, as she plans on never working a party again.

Phil calls Carol repeatedly. She has to admit that she likes him and finally agrees to go out with him. They have a fun relationship but she can't stand that his job always seems to get in the way. He stands her up on her birthday and she lets Mildred talk her into going to a party with her as a form of revenge on Phil. Carol agrees.

At the party, Carol sees that Phil is working, too. He tries to talk to her but she avoids him by latching onto a man named Cunningham. She asks him for a dance and he agrees, as long as they go out for some air first. He gets fresh with Carol and she pushes him away. He hits a wall and falls down dead. Everyone at the party accuses her of killing the old man but Phil. He stays true to her and takes her home. Carol is pleased to learn later that Cunningham suffered a heart attack at that moment and she won't face charges. In the end, she learns that Phil may stand her up but he'll also stand by her.

description:
Origin

Jerry is a regular blue collar guy looking for his big break.

Major Story Arcs

Jerry begins courting Drusilla Parrish. He learns that she is the daughter of a wealthy newspaper owner and he plans to marry her in order to get an important job in the family business. He uses intense passion to prove to Drusilla that they are in love and she agrees to marry him. The fact is, however, that he is in love with Betty Jones. He doesn't know that Drusilla finds out about Jerry's double life and he gets upset when Drusilla stands him up at the alter. He flees town in shame and drinks himself to death despite Betty being completely willing to take him in.

deck: Half-brother to Jerry Norwood.
description:
Origin

Half-brother to Jerry Norwood who is marrying Drusilla Parrish.

Major Story Arcs

When Tony hears that Jerry is getting married he hurries to Apple City to join in the festivities. Unbeknownst to Tony he bumps into Jerry's fiance Drusilla and the two share a moment. Jerry gets stood up at the alter and Tony goes back home without ever meeting Jerry's fiance.

Tony gets an idea to shame Jerry's fiance by wooing her and then standing her up at the alter. He goes back to Apple City and finds Drusilla. He is surprised to see that it is the same girl he shared that moment with before. No matter, as he rushes the relationship and makes Drusilla fall madly in love with him. He convinces her to marry him.

Two days before the wedding Jerry kills himself. Tony is so grieved that he confronts Drusilla about it all and breaks up with her. He informs her that he meant to break her heart but he just can't bring himself to do it anymore. He intends on leaving but finds a letter written Betty Jones, Jerry's girl-on-the-side that explains how Jerry had been playing Drusilla all along. Tony goes to the chapel on the day of their marriage and is elated that Drusilla still shows up. They get married.

Owner of Apple City's largest newspaper.

Major Story Arcs

Despite his reservations about the matter, Mr. Parrish supports his daughter Drusilla in her decision to get married after hardly knowing the fiance, Jerry Norwood. Drusilla doesn't go through with the wedding and begins courting another man. Mr. Parrish hears of Jerry's death and tries to get Drusilla to tell her new beau about her past. Things work out and Mr. Parrish is pleased to finally walk his daughter down the aisle at her wedding.

Origin

Wife of Mr. Parrish, the owner of the largest newspaper in town. Mother of Drusilla, a girl with the reputation of being a flirt.

Major Story Arcs

Because of her social status and how her daughter's actions reflect upon the family, Mrs. Parrish is constantly checking with Drusilla to make sure that she is doing things for the right reasons. Despite Drusilla's inability to appreciate how engagements are supposed to be done she supports her daughter in her various marriage situations.

name: Mrs. Parrish

deck: Daughter of a wealthy man and an incredible flirt.
description:
Origin

Drusilla's father owned the largest newspaper in their small midwestern town. She was spoiled and became a flighty flirt.

Major Story Arcs

Growing bored of the townee boys, Drusilla is swept off her feet by Jerry Norwood, a guy that falls in love with her and proposes marriage after a very short amount of time. Drusilla is not sure but agrees to marry him anyway. They set the date just a month ahead.

Betty Jones offers to throw Drusilla a party. Drusilla arrives early and finds Jerry and Betty kissing. Jerry explains that he is only marrying Drusilla so that her dad can give him a good job. Drusilla leaves the two but later returns when the party is in full swing. She is congratulated by the attendees but she feels like a fool. She leaves early and bumps into a stranger outside. Despite the fleeting moment together she remembers him. She has second thoughts about the wedding but decides not to tell anyone about what she overheard at Betty's house. She jilts Jerry at the alter on the day of the wedding. Jerry skips town to avoid the harsh gossip going around.

Three months later, the stranger arrives in town and meets Drusilla. He is Tony Abbott and the two begin dating. After a quick courting Tony proposes. Drusilla is madly in love and agrees. She wants to elope then and there but Tony talks her into have a traditional wedding.

While preparing for her wedding news reaches Drusilla of Jerry's death. The rumors seem to point to him drinking himself to death following being stood up at the alter. Tony takes Drusilla out for a drive and confronts her about Jerry. She learns that Jerry was Tony's half brother. She is mortified to hear that Tony was planning on jilting her as she had done to Jerry but he just can't do it now. Drusilla tries to explain that Jerry never loved her but Tony won't listen. She drives home alone with a broken heart.

She doesn't tell anyone the wedding is off and shows up to the church anyways. She walks down the aisle and finds Tony waiting for her. He explains that he found a letter from Betty to Jerry that explained everything.

deck: Petty resident of Apple City and true love of Jerry Norwood.
description:
Origin

An old school acquaintance of Drusilla Parrish.

Major Story Arcs

Betty is heartbroken when she hears that the love of her life, Jerry Norwood, is going to marry Drusilla Parrish. Despite her bitterness, Betty throws Drusilla a linens party for the wedding. Before the party Betty meets with Jerry and he explains that the only reason he is marrying Drusilla is to get a good job with her wealthy father. The two make out while, unbeknownst to them, Drusilla watches.

Betty is further heartbroken when Drusilla cancels the wedding and Jerry skips town without her. Despite writing a passionate letter to Jerry he drinks himself to death.

name: Betty Jones

deck: A dashing celebrity.
description:
Origin

Kirk is a celebrity who is reportedly engaged to another celebrity, Mimi Larson.

Major Story Arcs

One fine morning at the Sun Valley ski resort, Kirk runs headlong into Arlene Ellis. He compliments her on her looks and then leans in for a kiss, talking Arlene completely by surprise. He is in a hurry but promises to meet back with her in that same spot the next day. He is upset when she doesn't show up and he asks around the resort to see if anyone knows who she could have been. He is finally tipped off that she is the secretary for Mrs. Carter Dudley and they have flown off to Palm Beach in Florida. He follows her.

Kirk finds Arlene on the beach and tries to convince her to give him a shot. Arlene asks him about his relationship with Mimi Larson and he explains that it is completely one-sided - a publicity stunt on her part. He informs Arlene that he will meet her at the pool in the morning; he has people watching Arlene's routine. He is once again thwarted but his "spies" inform him that the ladies are sailing to Italy. He books the same passage.

He finds Arlene on the boat and the two get swept up in each other. They agree to marry when the boat docks and they will take Mrs. Dudley around Europe for their honeymoon.

name: Kirk Martingale

deck: Fiance of Kay Brandon and constantly changing their wedding date.
description:
Origin

A government engineer engaged to Kay Brandon. He constantly changes their wedding date. He lives in a hotel.

Major Story Arcs

To prove the next marriage date is for real, Roy takes Kay out to find their future home. They find one and head to his hotel to celebrate. A telegram arrives and notifies Roy that his father needs an operation immediately. He immediately flies home.

At home, Roy learns that his parents are stretched pretty thin. He gives them all his money and then flies back to Washington. He has to break the news to Kay that he needs to postpone their wedding again. He feels strongly that they need to start their marriage on a good foundation. Kay is unsure but trusts him.

Later, one of Kay's friends gets married. Kay is mocked and Roy tries to calm her down. He is shocked when she breaks up with him then and there. He decides to leave her alone for a while to let her cool down. He sees her some time later at a table with Michael Dodd, a rich kid. He confronts her and accuses her of being a floozy just looking to get hitched. He watches the two leave.

Kay's friend Ruth approaches Roy and tells him about her meddling. It was she who set Kay up on the date with Michael. She then tells Roy about Kay's accident - Michael had gotten so mad that Kay refused to marry him that he drove them off a bridge. Roy rushes to the hospital and admits to why he is always postponing he and Kay's wedding: his father was always angry that his mother pressured a fast marriage while the mother was always angry that his father wasn't the best provider. He promises that he is over this fear and wants to get married right away, trusting that their love is all the security he needs.

Midge and another friend Ruth try to convince Kay to branch out and date around. Midge proves that the idea works when she arrives home to announce to Kay and Ruth that she is engaged. Sure enough, Midge is married shortly thereafter while Kay delays her wedding date yet again.

deck: An impassioned rich kid who falls too easily in love.
description:
Origin

A young man that has been in love and sworn that he would never love again.

Major Story Arcs

Michael meets Kay Brandon on a blind date and the two start dating. In the few days that they date he is offered a job in South America. The next time he takes Kay out he wants to tell her the great news. He is interrupted, however, by Roy Wakefield, Kay's old boyfriend/current fiance. To avoid a scene, Michael takes Kay out for a drive. He announces the job and is disappointed that Kay doesn't seem very enthusiastic. He explains that he will only take the job if she marries him. He is further shocked that she doesn't immediately say yes. He kisses her in hopes of winning her over but she finally refuses his offer. He gets so mad that he drives their car off a bridge. Neither are serioiusly hurt, but Michael doesn't see Kay anymore. (She goes off and marries Roy after all.)

name: Michael Dodd

deck: A girl seemingly doomed to an eternal engagement to her fiance Roy.
description:
Origin

A government worker engaged to Roy Wakefield, a government engineer.

Major Story Arcs

Despite Roy's inability to stick to a wedding date, Kay continued to love him. The two set another date and try to cement it by finding their future home. They find the perfect place and go to Roy's hotel to celebrate. Kay is dismayed when Roy announces he has to leave after receiving an urgent telegram about his father needing an operation. While he is away, Kay's friends Midge and Ruth give her grief about Roy's inability to settle down.

When Roy returns Kay begs him to marry her right away. He informs her that his parents needed help and he gave them all of his money. Kay gets angry and accuses him of not being as committed as she, but he explains that he just wants a good foundation for their marriage. Kay accepts this and goes home. At home, Midge announces that she is engaged. The wedding comes quickly and Kay hates that the other girls all laugh her to scorn. Roy tries to calm her down but she spontaneously breaks up with him. To help Kay rebound, Ruth sets her up on a double date for the very next night.

The next night, Kay meets Michael, a handsome and suave man. They go on a few dates and enjoy each other's company. Ruth tries to warn Kay that Michael can be pretty high-strung but to no avail. One night, Michael has news but gets interrupted when Roy shows up at their dinner table. He accuses Kay of being a gold digger. She is hurt and follows Michael out. She learns what Michael is so giddy about while on a drive. He asks her to marry him. She gets confused at the suddenness of it all, especially after learning that Michael has taken a job in South America and wants to take her with him. She declines his request and he gets angry. He drives their car off a bridge.

Kay wakes up in the hospital pretty banged up. She laments to Ruth how she has lost Roy forever. Ruth explains that she found Roy and had a chat with him. Roy then enters the room and admits to why he is always postponing their wedding: his father was always angry that his mother pressured a fast marriage while the mother was always angry that his father wasn't the best provider. Roy just wanted to ensure neither of those things happened with he and Kay. Kay agrees to marry him again.

name: Kay Brandon

deck: Friend and coworker of Kay Brandon.
description:
Origin

A government worker in Washington with friends Kay Brandon and Midge.

Major Story Arcs

Like Midge, Ruth likes nothing more than to rib Kay about her relationship with Roy Wakefield. The girls just want Kay to dump him since he can never stick to a wedding date. Ruth takes it one step further, however, by setting Kay up on a blind date. Kay gets angry when Midge gets married first so she breaks up with Roy. Ruth comforts her and explains that she'll set Kay up with a guy named Michael Dodd the very next evening. Ruth gets nervous later on when it seems that Kay is leading this new guy on and she warns Kay that Michael is pretty high strung. She is appalled to hear that Michael goes crazy after Kay refuses to marry him and drives the two off a bridge. Ruth finds Roy and explains to him of her meddling and convinces him to take Kay back. She is happy to see that Roy does.

deck: An agent of S.H.I.E.L.D. who is a close friend of Emily Preston and Deadpool.
description:
Creation

Agent Scott Adsit debuted in the first issue of Marvel NOW! relaunched Deadpool series. His name and physical appearance are based on those of a real-life stand-up comedian Scott Adsit who is a close friend of series' writers Brian Posehn and Gerry Duggan.

While working with Preston and Deadpool, Adsit dealt with many threats, such as betrayal from within, multiple attacks from ULTIMATUM, murderous ex-Presidents and assassins rampaging through the streets of New York.

When investigating the murder of the Watcher, an explosion of energy caught Adsit in a field of debris. His right eye was severely injured.. He saw the fate of Deadpool's parents; they were killed by Deadpool. The mercenary was not acting in his right mind; he was being controlled by Butler, a scientist who had influenced Deadpool for years

At one time, a hacker stole the personal information of all working SHIELD agents. The hacker had crisis of conscience and tried to leave with the Avenger Hawkeye. Adsit's friends Deadshot and Preston's family became mixed up with the situation; despite this Adsit was assigned to the situation in a professional capacity. The information was later secured. .

Adsit's life with Deadpool led to his making many new friends, which included Ellie, Deadpool's daughter; the ghost of Benjamin Franklin and Michael, a Scottish wizard.

As a friend of Deadpool, Adsit was targeted for assassination by a re-organized ULTIMATUM. He killed the team sent after him but was severely wounded himself.

description:
Origin

Oswald Zinn, also known as Napoleon, used to be a great bank robber. This made him rich, but then he started hiring crews and planning the back robberies for them, this made him very rich. Then one day, after fifteen years of working behind the scene, one of his crews went rogue and killed a woman cop during a robbery. This got the attention of Punisher, who tracked the crew back to their hideout. He then started to fallow the money and this lead back to Oswald.

Oswald hires the Immortals, a band of mercenaries, and send them and his head body guard Billy to take down the Punsiher. This only works at making Punisher more angry. He tortures Billy and uses the information to come after Zinn personally. Zinn surrounds himself with hired guns but knows its only a matter of time. He is then approached by Gottlieb, with an offer of the place called Erewhon. Zinn takes Gottlieb on his offer only to learn that Erewhon is real but it exists as a run down village in the middle of a South American jungle.

Major Story Arcs

Wolverine/Punisher

For more information see: Wolverine/Punisher

Ten Years Later- Oswald Zinn has joined Gottlieb and his group called The Council. He devises a plan, break Harvey Long out of prison and use him to lure The Punisher to Ereworn. Then realize the citizens on the Punisher. This plan back fires and the citizens turn on the Council killing all but Zinn. He survives by promising the citizen the death of the Punisher.

He devises a plot that will force the Punisher to fight Wolverine to the death but this plan backfires and The Punisher kills Zinn.

Origin

Harvey Long is a contract killer who was caught, and prepared to testify against his employers. Before he could testify he was mysterious broken out of prison. He was then approached by Gottlieb, and offered a place in Erewhon.

Major Story Arcs

Wolverine/ Punisher

For more information see: Wolverine/Punisher

Harvey is broken out of prison and used as bait, by Oswald Zinn, to bring the Punisher to Erewhon. Unlike the other men Zinn used a bait, Harvey has been given a guardian angel, the X-man Wolverine. Zinn has set it up that the Punisher would be on Harvey's trail to kill him but Wolverine would be on his trail to bring him back to justice, where he would testify against his former crime bosses.

Harvey makes it close to Erewhone before he is attacked by the Punisher, and Wolverine saves Harvey's life. This leads to Wolverine and Punisher fighting it out in the jungle, while Harvey escapes to Erewhon. There he finds Zinn and Victoria. Harvey thinks he is safe but instead it is revealed he has out lived his usefulness and is quickly executed.

His severed head is then presented to the Father as a gift/ offering.
